There Is Always More to Learn

 
 
 
 
 

Think Twice Before Using Java 8 Parallel Streams 

If you listen to people from Oracle talking about design choices behind Java 8, you will often hear that parallelization was the driving force behind lambdas, stream APIs, and others.
However you should really think twice before applying parallel streams as in some scenarios they will become the main bottleneck of your application’s performance.

 
 
 
 
 
 

Five Command Line Options To Hack The Java Module System 

The Java Platform Module System (JPMS) not only comes with an entire set of new rules to abide by, it also introduces a host of command line options to break them. Whether you need to access internal APIs, or extend modules with classes of your own, they have you covered.
In this post you can go over the five most important command line options that you will need to get your project to compile, test, and run in the face of various migration challenges.

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

Preposition Preference 

Have you ever thought about how much we use prepositions in our Java APIs? When we use a preposition in an API, it should help convey meaning clearly. If it doesn’t, then we would have been better off without it. This article will guide you about the naming decisions you will be using, which is very important, especially if you are developing an API.

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

Is High Quality Software Worth the Cost? 

We are used to a trade-off between quality and cost. You might be surprised that this trade-off does not apply to software - high quality software is actually cheaper to produce.
Read more to find out why.

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

Continuous Delivery for Machine Learning 

Machine Learning applications are becoming popular in our industry, however the process for developing, deploying, and continuously improving them is more complex and harder to predict compared to more traditional software, such as a web service or a mobile application. They are subject to change in three axis: the code itself, the model, and the data.
See how you can bring Continuous Delivery principles and practices to Machine Learning applications. 

 
 
 
 
 

Serverless Java 

The intention behind the rise of serverless architecture is to abstract away all of the underlying infrastructure so you can focus on the code and the code only. You can develop your application faster and better and iterate faster than ever before.
Take a look at what solutions are available for developing serverless applications, or functions, with Java. 

 
 
 
 
 

Reactive Spring: Define a REST Endpoint as a Continuous Stream 

In the REST APIs, all Http requests are stateless. The connection between client and server is lost once the transaction ends, so 1 response for 1 request.
But sometimes, we get the requirement to have a continuous response for a single request. This continuous response is called Streaming response. So in this blog, we will see how we can do that in Spring.

 
 
 
 
 
 
 

Eclipse Microprofile Series 

Emerged from the legacy Java EE Microprofile intends to fix its predecessor issues by being more lightweight and combining only those specifications which the community considers necessary for developing microservices with Enterprise Java.

Let The Compiler do The Work for You! 

Take a look at how languages like Haskell enable you to easily solve some complex problems because of its powerful compiler compared to Java. This kind of powerful constructs is the main reason behind the excitement about new features coming to Java like records, sealed types and deconstruction patterns.

 
 
 
 
 
 

Crossing The JUnit Streams 

One of the nice things about JUnit 5 migration is that you can run your JUnit 4 tests in vintage mode and everything’s still compatible. However, some of the annotations and methods have the same name in JUnit 4 and JUnit 5 and it’s very easy, when both sets of the library dependencies are available, to import the wrong stuff and produce a test that doesn’t make work.

 
 
 
 
 

Modern Best Practices for Testing in Java 

Maintainable and readable test code is crucial to establish a good test coverage which in turn enables implementing new features and performing refactorings without the fear of breaking something. 
 This post involves modern technologies like JUnit5, AssertJ, Testcontainers, and Kotlin and contains many best practices that the author has collected over the years, writing unit and integration tests.

Java 8 Date/Time Kata 

The Calendar Kata is an advanced kata which can help you become familiar with the Java 8 Date/Time libraries. The domain for the Calendar kata is an object representation of an Outlook Calendar.
If you want to try it out, check out this repository!
